{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774409185,"nonce":"HPoGHzAn9JAhQDBQ6rUElue0YtM=","title":"Enforce translation invariance in network inputs for point-mass reaching","message":"The network currently receives absolute workspace coordinates (effector position, target position) as inputs. The point-mass dynamics (F=ma) are translation invariant — there are no position-dependent forces. Therefore identical reach vectors at different workspace locations should produce identical policies, but the network must learn this from data rather than having it enforced.\n\nProposed fix: express all position inputs relative to start position: (pos - start_pos) and (target - start_pos). The network sees only the reach vector and progress along it.\n\nFor point-mass systems, this loses no information and enforces a symmetry the dynamics already have. For future muscle/joint models, absolute workspace position matters (joint angles are workspace-dependent), so this invariance would need to be removed.\n\nThe current training workspace ([-1,1]^2) may mask generalization failures — the network could learn approximate invariance within this range but fail outside it.\n\nCross-ref: Bug: 61d3502 (experimental plan)","files":null}]}